<h1>Are Chocolate and Peanut Butter Cheerios Gluten-Free?</h1>

<p>For individuals with celiac disease or gluten sensitivity, finding safe and delicious breakfast options can be a challenge. One popular cereal that often comes into question is Cheerios, specifically the Chocolate and Peanut Butter Cheerios variety. In this article, we’ll dive deep into whether these tasty cereals are gluten-free, how they are made, and what you need to know before adding them to your diet.</p>

<h2>Understanding Gluten and Its Impact</h2>

<p>Gluten is a protein found in wheat, barley, rye, and triticale. For people with celiac disease, consuming gluten can trigger an immune response that damages the small intestine. Even small amounts of gluten can cause symptoms like bloating, diarrhea, and fatigue. Therefore, it’s crucial for those with gluten-related disorders to ensure that their food is free from gluten contamination.</p>

<p>Gluten-free diets have also gained popularity among individuals without celiac disease, often due to perceived health benefits or personal preferences. However, for those with celiac disease or gluten sensitivity, a gluten-free diet is not a choice but a necessity.</p>

<h2>Are Chocolate and Peanut Butter Cheerios Gluten-Free?</h2>

<p>General Mills, the manufacturer of Cheerios, claims that their Chocolate and Peanut Butter Cheerios are gluten-free. According to the company, they use a process to sort out gluten-containing grains from oats, which are naturally gluten-free but often contaminated during harvesting and processing. This process involves mechanical and optical sorting to remove any traces of wheat, barley, or rye.</p>

<p>However, it’s important to note that while the oats used in Cheerios are processed to remove gluten, there is still some debate within the gluten-free community about the safety of these products. Some individuals with celiac disease have reported adverse reactions after consuming Cheerios, leading to concerns about cross-contamination during the manufacturing process.</p>

<h2>How Cheerios Are Made Gluten-Free</h2>

<p>General Mills has developed a proprietary process to ensure that their Cheerios are gluten-free. Here’s a breakdown of the steps involved:</p>

<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Step</th>
            <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>1. Sourcing Oats</td>
            <td>Oats are sourced from suppliers who follow strict guidelines to minimize cross-contamination with gluten-containing grains.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>2. Mechanical Sorting</td>
            <td>Oats are mechanically sorted to remove any foreign grains, such as wheat, barley, or rye.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>3. Optical Sorting</td>
            <td>Advanced optical sorting technology is used to detect and remove any remaining gluten-containing grains.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>4. Testing</td>
            <td>Each batch of oats is tested to ensure that it contains less than 20 parts per million (ppm) of gluten, which is the FDA’s threshold for gluten-free labeling.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<p>Despite these rigorous steps, some experts argue that the process may not be foolproof, and there is still a risk of cross-contamination. This is why some individuals with celiac disease choose to avoid Cheerios altogether.</p>

